---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import factChecks from '../data/fact-checks.json';
import bibliography from '../data/bibliography.json';

const bibById = Object.fromEntries(bibliography.map((b) => [b.id, b]));
const fpvCheck = factChecks.find((f) => f.topic.includes('Kristal'));
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Lommel case study"
  description="Belgium silica hub, ecological reclamation, and renewable energy co-location — with verified corrections."
  current="lommel"
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero__eyebrow">Established model · Flanders, Belgium</p>
    <h1>Lommel and the Campine silica industry</h1>
    <p>
      Since the 19th century, Lommel has exploited exceptionally pure quartz sand (<em>zilverzand</em>),
      historically linked to firms such as Sibelco. High chemical purity (reported SiO₂ &gt; 99.5%,
      very low iron) supports Europe’s glass and advanced manufacturing supply chains through
      regional processing rather than raw export alone.
    </p>
  </section>

  <article class="card">
    <h2>Industrial clustering</h2>
    <p>
      The region retained value by coupling extraction with glass and chemical industries — a pattern
      Uganda’s policy discourse often references when discussing domestic sheet glass and packaging.
    </p>
    <p>
      <span class="tag">Corporate context</span>
      <a href={bibById['sibelco-lommel-history']?.url}>Sibelco</a> (verify operational details against independent planning documents).
    </p>
  </article>

  <article class="card">
    <h2>From degradation to the Lommelse Sahara</h2>
    <p>
      Early open-pit mining and related industry altered pine forests and hydrology. Planned
      post-mining restoration — conifer belts, flooded pits, heathland species — created the
      <strong>Lommelse Sahara</strong> nature area, now managed as a biodiversity asset.
    </p>
    <p>
      <a href={bibById['lommelse-sahara-natuurpunt']?.url}>Natuurpunt — Lommelse Sahara</a>
    </p>
  </article>

  <article class="card">
    <h2>Renewable energy: two distinct precedents</h2>
    <h3>Kristal Solar Park (ground-mounted)</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>99.5 MW</strong> photovoltaic plant on Kristalpark III, Lommel (~93 ha). Operational from 2019;
      supplies industry including Nyrstar under PPA arrangements. This is <em>not</em> a floating installation.
    </p>
    <p><a href={bibById['lommel-kristal-solar']?.url}>Stad Lommel — Kristal Solar Park</a></p>

    <h3>Floating PV on a Sibelco quarry lake (Mol/Dessel)</h3>
    <p>
      The <strong>Floating PV</strong> project (~7 MWp) on the De Schans sand quarry (Sibelco) demonstrates
      water-cooled PV, on-site industrial consumption, and land sparing — closer to the framework report’s
      “quarry lake” narrative than Kristal Solar Park.
    </p>
    <p><a href={bibById['sibelco-floating-pv']?.url}>floatingpv.be</a> · <a href={bibById['irena-fpv-2020']?.url}>IRENA floating solar outlook</a></p>
  </article>

  {fpvCheck && (
    <div class="notice">
      <strong>Fact-check ({fpvCheck.verified_status.replace('_', ' ')}):</strong>
      {fpvCheck.finding}
    </div>
  )}
</BaseLayout>
